HCI and Virtual Infrastructure Deployment

HCI simplifies IT by combining compute, storage, and memory in one system. It makes scaling up and managing resources easier and avoids complex storage setups.

HCI Deployment Characteristics

The key characteristics of HCI deployment are as follows:

  • Easy deployment: HCI systems are designed for straightforward installation and configuration. They integrate compute, storage, and networking into a single, unified platform, reducing the complexity of setting up traditional IT infrastructure. This simplicity often results in faster deployment times and fewer manual configurations.

  • Easy expansion: An HCI environment's modular design simplifies expansion. To scale up, more nodes can be added to the existing cluster. Each new node typically brings additional compute, storage, and networking resources, allowing linear scalability without significant reconfiguration.

  • Failure handling: HCI solutions include built-in redundancy and failover mechanisms to handle hardware failures. In the event of a failure, data and workloads are automatically redistributed across remaining nodes to ensure high availability and minimizing downtime without requiring complex manual intervention.

  • No-SAN network: Unlike traditional infrastructures that rely on separate SANs for storage, HCI eliminates the need for a dedicated SAN. Storage is directly integrated into the hyperconverged nodes, which streamlines architecture and reduces the costs associated with maintaining separate storage networks.

In HCI solutions, the minimum deployment typically involves three servers or nodes that collectively form a unified pool of compute, memory, and storage resources. As resource needs grow, you can scale up the environment by adding more drives to the existing servers or adding additional nodes. This process is straightforward: new servers are connected to the existing LAN and integrated via an expansion wizard, which simplifies the scaling process compared to traditional multi-tier infrastructures.

Similarly, the process for retiring or maintaining servers is streamlined. When a server is retired or taken offline for maintenance, the overall resource pool for VMs temporarily decreases. This situation does not affect workload performance, because the system's built-in redundancy and failover mechanisms ensure that operations continue smoothly even if a server fails or is removed from the pool. This approach allows for flexible scaling and maintenance while maintaining operational efficiency.

Another benefit of such a system is the deployment process. The deployment consists of preparing the infrastructure, such as top-of-rack (ToR) switches and various protocols, connecting servers to an upstream Ethernet connection, and running the installation wizard. There is no need to configure any SAN protocols such as Fibre Channel or Internet Small Computer Systems Interface (iSCSI), which makes the deployment of hyperconverged systems faster and easier.

Because a hyperconverged solution is a very flexible and relatively simple architecture in your data center, it can easily be the foundation for building your enterprise private cloud. You can start small and expand when needed, so you do not have to worry about overprovisioning or underprovisioning resources for your applications and business. The ability to expand by adding more nodes also removes the need for regular large-scale hardware upgrades.

HCI and Virtual Infrastructure Deployment Considerations

Deploying HCI and virtual infrastructure requires careful planning and consideration to ensure that the solution aligns with the organization's performance, security, scalability, and manageability needs.
